        heading:"Sensex, Nifty muted as IT stocks plunge on US recession fears",
        subheading:"The S&P BSE Sensex was trading 57.93 points lower at 60,334.84 at around 9:55 am, while the NSE Nifty 50 was down 0.12 per cent at 17,790.65.",
        description:"Benchmark stock market indices began the trading session on a weak note on Thursday after a plunge in IT stocks, triggered by fears of a “mild recession” in the US. The S&P BSE Sensex was trading 57.93 points lower at 60,334.84 at around 9:55 am, while the NSE Nifty 50 was down 0.12 per cent at 17,790.65. The broader markets also showed signs of weakness, in line with the benchmark indices. Sectoral indices were mixed, with the Nifty IT index emerging as the worst performer after falling 1.71 per cent. Nine of the 10 constituents comprising the IT index fell sharply. This comes just a day after TCS report its Q4 results. Although TCS reported a net profit of nearly 15 per cent, it flagged concerns of deferred spending and near-term uncertainty in its banking, financial services and insurance (BFSI) segment. TCS was down 1.71 per cent at around 10.15 am. Analysts said the unexpected weakness in the BFSI segment in the US took a toll on the company’s results. Major tech stocks like Infosys, Tech Mahindra, HCL Tech and Wipro were also trading in negative territory in the range of 1-2 per cent in early trade and were the top losers on the Nifty 50 index. While TCS’ results seem to have hit sentiments, a bigger jolt has come from a recession warning in the US, issued by the Federal Reserve. The US Federal Reserve has projected a mild recession later this year and it has further impacted IT stocks. But the impact of this on the broader markets was limited after positive domestic retail inflation data. In March, CPI-based inflation fell to 5.66 per cent, which is lower than the Reserve Bank of India's upper tolerance limit of 6 per cent. Meanwhile, Apollo Hospital was the top gainer on the Nifty 50 index, followed by Britannia Industries, Eicher Motors, HDFC Life and Nestle India. Among other stocks, AU Small Finance Bank jumped 10 per cent after the Reserve Bank of India reappointed its managing director and CEO. Domestic markets will be closed on Friday on account of Ambedkar Jayanti.",
